In 3.3.0 you can achieve the desired result by using a wildcard action when restricting the instance types. You would add something like the following to the policy in this issues description:

{code}
    {
      "Action": [
        "ec2:DescribeInstance*"
      ],
      "Effect": "Deny",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:ec2:::vmtype/m1.small",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:ec2:::vmtype/m1.large"
    },
{code}

Hey [~sjones],

Does this mean the following would work as well:

{code}
   {
      "Action": [
        "ec2:DescribeInstance*"
      ],
      "Effect": "Deny",
      "Resource": [
       "arn:aws:ec2:::vmtype/m1.small",
       "arn:aws:ec2:::vmtype/m1.large",
      ]
    },
{code}

Confirmed that in 4.0 you can add a policy as follows:

{code}
{
  "Statement": [
   {
      "Action": [
        "ec2:DescribeInstanceTypes"
      ],
      "Effect": "Deny",
      "Resource": [
       "arn:aws:ec2:::vmtype/m1.small",
       "arn:aws:ec2:::vmtype/m1.large"
      ]
    } ]
}
{code}

To deny access to specific vm types for an account or a user (if the user has another policy granting access)
